# Rename specific columns using rename() from dplyr
data <- data %>%
  rename(
    Treatment = "Pos..Control..No.Rx...A..A.SA..B..B.SB..combination.of.A.and.B..combination.of.SA.and.SB",
    Replicate = "Replicate",
    Tube = "Slide..tube.....for.use.in.lab.",
    ResponseNoChange = "Response..No.change.in.morphology..No.GT..PH.or.buds.",
    ResponseGT = "Response..GT..germtubes..only",
    ResponsePH = "Response..Pseudohypha..PH..only",
    ResponseBuds = "Response..Buds.only",
    ResponseGTPH = "Response..GT...PH",
    ResponseGTBuds = "Response..GT...Buds",
    ResponsePHBuds = "Response..PH...Buds",
    ResponseGTMultiple = "Response...1.GTs.multiple.GTs."
  )
# Calculate proportions for each response variable based on 200 total cells per replicate
data <- data %>%
  mutate(ResponseNoChangeProp = ResponseNoChange / 200,
         ResponseGTProp = ResponseGT / 200,
         ResponsePHProp = ResponsePH / 200,
         ResponseBudsProp = ResponseBuds / 200,
         ResponseGTPHProp = ResponseGTPH / 200,
         ResponseGTBudsProp = ResponseGTBuds / 200,
         ResponsePHBudsProp = ResponsePHBuds / 200,
         ResponseGTMultipleProp = ResponseGTMultiple / 200)
summary_data <- data %>%
  group_by(Treatment) %>%
  summarise(
    MeanResponseGT = mean(ResponseGTProp),
    SDResponseGT = sd(ResponseGTProp),
    MeanResponseNoChange = mean(ResponseNoChangeProp),
    SDResponseNoChange = sd(ResponseNoChangeProp),
    MeanResponsePH = mean(ResponsePHProp),
    SDResponsePH = sd(ResponsePHProp),
    MeanResponseBuds = mean(ResponseBudsProp),
    SDResponseBuds = sd(ResponseBudsProp),
    MeanResponseGTPH = mean(ResponseGTPHProp),
    SDResponseGTPH = sd(ResponseGTPHProp),
    MeanResponseGTBuds = mean(ResponseGTBudsProp),
    SDResponseGTBuds = sd(ResponseGTBudsProp),
    MeanResponsePHBuds = mean(ResponsePHBudsProp),
    SDResponsePHBuds = sd(ResponsePHBudsProp),
    MeanResponseGTMultiple = mean(ResponseGTMultipleProp),
    SDResponseGTMultiple = sd(ResponseGTMultipleProp)
  ) %>%
  # Format mean  SD for each response category
  mutate(
    GT = paste0(round(MeanResponseGT, 2), "  ", round(SDResponseGT, 2)),
    NoChange = paste0(round(MeanResponseNoChange, 2), "  ", round(SDResponseNoChange, 2)),
    PH = paste0(round(MeanResponsePH, 2), "  ", round(SDResponsePH, 2)),
    Buds = paste0(round(MeanResponseBuds, 2), "  ", round(SDResponseBuds, 2)),
    GTPH = paste0(round(MeanResponseGTPH, 2), "  ", round(SDResponseGTPH, 2)),
    GTBuds = paste0(round(MeanResponseGTBuds, 2), "  ", round(SDResponseGTBuds, 2)),

Plan to do for the final/full analysis:

This analysis employs orthogonal contrasts to examine the impact of various treatments on hyphal formation in Candida albicans, focusing on testing each hypothesis independently while minimizing Type I error rates associated with multiple comparisons. Orthogonal contrasts ensure that each comparison is distinct and non-overlapping, allowing for a robust interpretation of the treatment effects on hyphal formation.

For the first hypothesis, a contrast vector [-7, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1] was defined to compare the untreated control group to the seven treatment groups combined. Here, the control is assigned a weight of -7, while each treatment group receives a weight of 1. This contrast tests whether the treatments as a group reduce hyphal formation relative to the control.

In the second hypothesis, the contrast vector [0, 0, 1, 1, -1, -1, 0, 0] compares the effectiveness of treatments containing Compound A to those containing Compound B. Treatments containing Compound A receive a weight of 1, those with Compound B are assigned -1, and other treatments are excluded from the comparison with a weight of 0. This setup tests if treatments with Compound A reduce hyphal formation more than those with Compound B.

For the third hypothesis, the contrast vector [0, 6, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1] was constructed to isolate the Aloe extract treatment and compare it against all other treatments combined. The Aloe extract treatment is given a weight of 6, while all other treatments receive a weight of -1. This contrast tests if the Aloe extract has a uniquely distinct impact on hyphal formation compared to the other treatments.

# Define the orthogonal contrast matrix
contrast_matrix <- matrix(c(
    -7,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,    # Control vs. All Treatments
     0,  0,  1,  1, -1, -1,  0,  0,    # Compound A vs Compound B
     0,  6, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1     # Aloe Extract vs. Other Treatments
), ncol = 3, byrow = FALSE)

# Assign contrast names to the matrix
colnames(contrast_matrix) <- c("Control_vs_AllTreatments", "CompoundA_vs_CompoundB", "Aloe_vs_Others")

# Check orthogonality by calculating pairwise products (dot products)
orthogonality_check <- t(contrast_matrix) %*% contrast_matrix
print("Orthogonality Check:")
## [1] "Orthogonality Check:"
print(orthogonality_check)

Below is a sample code to set up the orthogonal contrast matrix and perform the planned analysis. This code demonstrates the approach without running inferential tests, as the intention is only to outline the analysis plan.

Sample Code for Future Plan

# Ensure 'Treatment' is a factor with specified levels
data$Treatment <- factor(data$Treatment, 
                         levels = c("No Treatment (positive control)", 
                                    "Whole Aloe arborescens Extract", 
                                    "compound 'A' isolated from Aloe arborescens", 
                                    "compound 'A-SA' from Sigma Aldrich", 
                                    "compound 'B' isolated from Aloe arborescens", 
                                    "compound 'B-SA' from Sigma Aldrich", 
                                    "combination of A and B", 
                                    "combination of A-SA and B-SA"))


# Define the orthogonal contrast matrix
contrast_matrix <- matrix(c(
    -7,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  1,    # Control vs. All Treatments
     0,  0,  1,  1, -1, -1,  0,  0,    # Compound A vs Compound B
     0,  6, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1     # Aloe Extract vs. Other Treatments
), ncol = 3, byrow = FALSE)

# Assign contrast names to the matrix
colnames(contrast_matrix) <- c("Control_vs_AllTreatments", "CompoundA_vs_CompoundB", "Aloe_vs_Others")

# Apply the contrasts explicitly using the `contrasts<-` function
contrasts(data$Treatment) <- contrast_matrix

# Fit the model with the specified contrasts
model <- lm(ResponseGTProp ~ Treatment, data = data)
